The '''178th New York Volunteer Infantry Regiment''' was an [[Infantry]] [[Regiment]] that served in the United States Army during the [[American Civil War]]. It was often referred to as the [[Zouaves#Zouaves of the United States of America and of the Confederate States of America|"''Second Regiment, Hawkins Zouaves''"]].

==Military Service, 1863==
{{Empty section|date=July 2010}}
==Military Service, 1864==
{{Empty section|date=July 2010}}
==Military Service, 1865==
The regiment was mustered out of service on April 20, 1866, at Montgomery, Alabama, under the command of Lieutenant Colonel John B. Gandolfo.

==Casualties==
The regiment suffered the following casualties during its service.<br />
* '''Killed In Action''': 0 Officers, 9 Enlisted
* '''Died of Wounds''': 0 Officers, 9 Enlisted
* '''Died of Disease and other causes''': 2 Officers, 190 Enlisted (35 Died as POW's)
* '''Total''': 2 Officers and 208 Enlisted.

==Commanding officers==
* Lieutenant Colonel John B. Gandolfo

